                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d440">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/2735a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in France</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Shaw</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase<note n="40" xml:id="d440fn40">Quotations
                            not paraphrased.</note>]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-11-17T19:00:00-05:00"
                            >November 17, 1931—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>559. For Ambassador Dawes: <list>
                        <label>(1)</label>
                        <item>On November 17 the <hi rend="italic">New York Herald-Tribune</hi>
                            carried an article, dated Washington, November 16, which stated “it was
                            learned tonight on high official authority” that “At no time in the
                            negotiations … was [Katsuji Debuchi,] the Japanese Ambassador left
                            without confidence that the American Government would refuse to follow
                            the League of Nations either in a proposed economic boycott of Japanese
                            exports, withdrawal of world diplomatic representatives from Tokio or
                            insistence upon the withdrawal of Japanese troops from occupied
                            Manchurian territory by today.”</item>
                        <label>(2)</label>
                        <item>No statement nor commitment has been made by the Department regarding
                            its attitude in connection with a boycott of Japanese <pb facs="0577"
                                n="467" xml:id="pg_467"/> exports or the withdrawal from Tokyo of
                            diplomatic representatives. You are informed fully of the Department’s
                            attitude regarding the withdrawal of Japanese troops.</item>
                        <label>(3)</label>
                        <item>The same article has the following subheading: “Utmost Support Pledged
                            to Geneva Disavowed by State Department in Conferences With Debuchi.”
                            There is, as you are aware, no basis for such a statement.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
